Natural song from one of several unseen birds in dense understory of subtropical/upper tropical forest upslope from road (a P. guy was seen well feeding on flowers beside road here). The song is rather unlike other cuts of P. guy I've heard, and sounds more like P. koepckeae, but as far as I know, that latter species is unknown from the Afluente area, so that leaves me with P. guy, unless perhaps P. malaris gives a song like this in San Martin (and is present so high here).

Locality: El Dorado Lodge, Santa Marta, Magdalena
Remarks:
Assumed to be this species, though for some time a mystery to me.  At first believed to be an aberrant violetear song, but upon comparison with various hummer/hermit songs on XC, now believed to be GcH.   Two birds singing some 25 m apart from each other, neither individual found, even after prolonged search. 

I am not confident this species occurs in the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta, but this is not the only recording of it at this location.
